Jeremy Corbyn to debut on Prime Minister's Questions
Since his election, Mr. Corbyn’s debut at PMQ has been highly anticipated.
New job leader Jeremy Corbyn will have his debut in Prime Minister's Questions later, and for the first time he will have to collaborate with David Cameron.
Mr. Corbyn will ask the first of his six assigned questions shortly after noon, while his performance is likely to be carefully examined by the media and MPs.
In a weekly statement, he called for "less theatre and more facts."
He also said he could skip several sessions that he would leave to his colleagues.
This meeting will be the first parliamentary test of Mr. Corby’s leadership, which comes after his appointment to the Shadow Cabinet and his Tuesday speech at the annual TUC Congress.
Meanwhile, the Labour leader’s decision to remain silent during the singing of the national anthem in service on Tuesday on the occasion of the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Britain has met criticism from a number of Conservative MPs and is the focus of several stories on the headlines of the newspapers.
Mr. Corbyn’s decision not to sing the national anthem attracted attention.
Mr. Corbyn's spokesman said he would "stand in respectful silence" and that he would recognize "the heroism of the Royal Air Force in the battle for Britain."
However, Mr. Corbyn’s shadow cabinet member, Owen Smith, told BBC Two’s Newsnight that he would recommend Labour leader sing the national anthem “no matter” his belief that the monarchy should be abolished.
Nearly a dozen shadow ministers refused to serve in Mr Corbyn's top team, citing differences in economy, defense and foreign affairs, and only less than a sixth of the parliamentary party originally supported him as a leader.
BBC Political Correspondent Robin Brant says political differences in work are also "changing" after Mr. Corbyn's appointment despite his position in the European Union and the government's benefit limit.
Mr. Corbyl stated at the TUC conference that the Labour Party had submitted amended proposals to remove the entire idea of the benefit limit.
A few hours later, Mr. Smith, secretary of shadow work and pensions, stated that the party “very clearly” opposed the government’s plans to lower the limit from £26,000 to £23,000.
Mr. Corbyn will be the fifth Labour leader David Cameron has faced in the last decade since he was elected Conservative leader.
The leader of the Labour Party, who promised a different approach to politics, claims to have ideas “from the crowd” on questions for Mr. Cameron and received more than 30,000 proposals.
MP Islington North claims that PMQs are too confrontational and that they will refrain from both “fast response” and tooth trade, and instead promise to focus on important issues such as poverty, inequality and the challenges facing young people.
Mr. Corbyn claims that Angela Eagle, the shadow trade secretary, will represent him at the PMQ when he does not attend — such as when Mr. Cameron travels abroad.
He also refrained from the idea of allowing other colleagues to speak for him from time to time because he was told he had discussed the matter with House spokesman John Bercow.
When Mr. Cameron became leader in 2005, he said he wanted to deviate from the style of politics "Punch and Judy," which was often associated with the PMQ, but a few years later admitted he had failed.
Since its first broadcast in 1990, PMQs have been seen as a key barometer of leaders’ judgment, their House leadership, and their attitude among other MPs, although critics have argued that they have become a cartoon and need far-reaching reforms.
