Multiple sclerosis: it depends not only on medications, but also on the patient’s will to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complicated disease and a person with this diagnosis needs the care of a number of specialists: a neurologist, physiotherapist, ergotherapist, urologist, ophthalmologist, psychologist, psychiatrist and many other specialists.
However, it is not only medical care, for example, women with multiple sclerosis need consultation if they decide to have a child, social-legal advice, recommendations for adjusting housing, etc. are included in the care of these sick people.
Nevertheless, all this is not enough: the development of the disease can fundamentally affect the patient himself.
The more he will actively fight the disease, the longer he can work and may not fundamentally change his lifestyle.
As doctors point out, the passivity of the sick free up space for the activity of the disease.
For example, it has been shown that regular movement significantly delays the time when a sick person needs some compensatory aid, such as a rod.
It is important that patients and their surroundings are not subject to various myths, for example, that the disease automatically leads them to end up on a wheelchair.
This is why the website “Get a Chance” (www.bezmytu.cz) was created, which is supported by the ongoing media campaign “Get a Chance”.
The most important person in the care of a patient with multiple sclerosis is a neurologist.
In multiple sclerosis, it is said twice that the sooner the disease begins to be treated, the more the doctor can influence something.
This is because we have medicines for multiple sclerosis in the inflammatory stage, when the neurodegeneration process is not yet so strong.
The sooner we intervene, the greater the hope that we can stop the disease and delay disability, explains Dr. Eva Medová of the Neurological Clinic of the General Faculty Hospital in Prague.
Very important is for people with multiple sclerosis rehabilitation care, which most often solves weakening of the lower limbs or imbalance disorders.
We work with patients according to their individual needs: to maintain fitness, improve walking, strengthen the pelvic floor, alleviate swallowing disorders or improve coordination.
"It is really individual, it depends on the specific difficulties of the patient," says MUDr. Martina Kövári, primary of the Clinic of Rehabilitation and Fitness Medicine of the Faculty Hospital in Motola.
People with multiple sclerosis suffer from the same disease, but each person manifests itself in a different way.
Rehabilitation cannot stop the disease, but it can always alleviate its symptoms.
Movement activity, however, also strengthens the immune state of the organism, which is desirable in the case of multiple sclerosis.
Another positive thing about regular exercise is the fact that the sick check what they can do, and this strengthens their self-confidence.
"During exercise, endorphins are also discharged and a person feels good after it," says Dr. Kamila Řasová of the Clinic of Rehabilitation Medicine of the Royal Vinohrad Faculty Hospital.
By influencing the physical side, we act on the limbic system responsible for emotions.
Directly, we interfere with the psyche and immune processes and stabilize the disease.
"In the past, these patients were so-called saving, today we know that they need a targeted load," says Prof. PaedDr. Pavel Kolář, head of the Clinic of Rehabilitation and Fitness Medicine of the Faculty Hospital in Motola.
The goal of physiotherapy is to allow a person to remain self-sufficient for as long as possible, including work.
Therefore, physiotherapists cooperate with ergotherapists so that each person receives a compensatory aid tailored to him.
Many patients need psychiatric or psychiatric care.
They are in a difficult life situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, most people are shocked by it.
They experience shock, panic, fear.
It has to respond to a great burden - the loss of health.
With such a painful soul, we must go to someone, not try to carry everything on our own shoulders.
"I work with them so that they eventually come to the conclusion that even with a disability you can live a full life and that multiple sclerosis does not mean the end of life," says psychotherapist Renata Malinová-Schubert from the Neurological Clinic of the General Faculty Hospital in Prague.
