Parliament voted for a greater share of coal taxes.
The change in mining fees is expected to bring to the state treasury 427 million crowns more than in 2013.
The government has a neutral impact on municipal budget revenues, as the fee is expected to be higher.
In the previous year, the municipalities received approximately 450 million crowns from fees and 150 million crowns from the state budget.
From the mining of brown coal, the municipalities spent about 200 million kronor and the state 66 million.
The new law also envisages an increase in the allowance for extraction of land to 1,000 crowns per hectare per year.
The revenue from these payments will continue to belong in full to the municipalities.
Minister of Industry Jan Mládek (ČSSD) told the MPs that municipalities will receive annually, instead of 14 million to 100 million crowns.
The amount of mining fees will no longer be determined by law, but will be determined by the government by its decree.
The reimbursement shall be newly calculated as a combination of the amount of extracted mineral and the rate for the individual types of minerals.
According to the government, the reason for the change is, among other things, the possibility of a flexible response to the current economic situation.
But ODS member Marek Benda warned that the establishment of the fee by a government decree may not be in accordance with the Constitution.
According to the Minister, however, this is not a tax in this case, because the state charges the mineral, which is the state property.
Only municipalities whose territories are affected by mining receive fees.
In the case of deep coal mining, three-quarters of the money will be given to the municipality and a quarter to the state.
The same is true of radioactive mining.
Part of the money collected by the state on mining fees will be targeted.
For example, 28 percent will have to go to repair damage after mining or to provide mining rescue services.
The proposal was criticized by opposition lawmakers, wholy argued that it would damage the communities affected by the mining and the counties.
For example, Michal Kučera (TOP 09 and Mayors) warned that mining firms will no longer want to sponsor municipalities as before, because they will pay higher fees directly to the state budget.
"It is not possible to tunnel one of the poorest regions just to make the Minister of Finance improve the budget," said David Kádner (Usvit) elected in Ústecký kraj.
From the rise of unemployment in Mostecko warned MP Hana Aulická.
Kádner and Aulická unsuccessfully proposed to reject the novel, Kučera wanted to return the law to the government for completion.
The reasoning report says that according to the mining companies, the increase in taxes will not affect coal prices, because prices are more than 90 percent long-term negotiated.
Major consumers such as power plants or heat plants should therefore not feel the price rise.
"On the other hand, however, this fact increases the risk that mining organizations will compensate for the increase in payments by trying to reduce their operating expenses, which would mean a reduction in the number of employees," the government admits.
However, he believes that the increase in taxes is acceptable.
According to Milan Urban (ČSSD), the rapporteur on the novel, it is crucial that the MPs know the conclusions about the updated energy concept and especially the government’s decision on coal mining limits before the bill is approved.
