“Sonogenetics” or control of brain cells using sound waves
This video shows how sound impulses affect the direction in which the speakers move.
Scientists have raised worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can control sound waves.
The small signals change direction when they are hit by sound impulses that are unheard for the human ear.
The pulses work by switching cells of genetically modified motor neurons that are programmed to respond to these ultrasound waves.
Scientists can read and record brain activity using light
The scientists said these worms are a great demonstration of a new method called sonogenetics, which uses ultrasound to activate brain, heart, and muscle cells and activate outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that this method could one day replace deep brain stimulation – an invasive procedure in which electrodes are injected into a patient’s brain to stimulate the brain.
Helmets usually do not respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that the reaction came when they were placed in a fluid containing microscopic bubbles.
As he found, bubbles intensify ultrasound waves, which then pass through the body of worms.
Enhanced ultrasound waves act in the TRP-4 ion channels, which are located in the membranes of some worm cells.
Thanks to sound waves, these channels open and activate the cells with which they are connected, according to a report in the journal Nature Communications.
In order to control the signals using ultrasonic waves, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motor neurons contained TRP-4 ion channels.
When he then applied ultrasound to the modified worms, the sound waves were amplified by micro-bubbles and transferred to the worms, where modified motor neurons were turned on.
The new method is much like optogenetics, a pioneering tool that allows scientists to turn on and off neurons using light.
Chalasani said that sonogenetics could have many advantages over this technique.
Unlike light, which must be sent by optical fiber to the desired place in the brain, ultrasound waves can penetrate tissues without restriction and be sent directly to the brain.
“We believe that when we use gene therapy and therapeutic viruses, we can target human neurons and make them temporarily sensitive to ultrasound signals used in clinical treatment to treat neurological diseases,” Chalasani said.
He added that the method would also be used in the treatment of muscle cells and insulin-producing cells.
