Have flourishes been breakfast champions for tens of thousands of years?
In the Italian Grotta Paglicci, archaeologists managed to find a discovery that opens up interesting possibilities.
They discovered traces of settlement by modern man from different times, including wall paintings, remnants of tools, and so on, and so on.
In the layer 23A, which is dated to about 30 thousand years ago, scientists have discovered something very similar to the remains of a breakfast buffet.
In fact, traces of oatmeal were found on the site, which apparently went through the process of producing today so popular flour.
At this time, the grains are first soaked, then dried, removed from the packaging, the so-called plough, then spared and scattered.
In the Paglicci cave, grains were discovered, which were apparently heated or spared, and then apparently crushed between two millstones - at least this is indicated by the traces of use on two stones in the cave.
The scientists were therefore unable to demonstrate in their publication for PNAS that a complete process of flour production would take place in the cave, but the similarity is actually very noticeable.
We also don’t have any evidence of how people could have eaten flour, but the assumption that it was with some liquid and maybe even warm, of course, is quite logical.
At the same time, it is a very interesting proof of how intensely people used cereals long before the emergence of agriculture.
If the flower interpretation is correct, the oldest flakes have surpassed agriculture by approximately 20,000 years.
