The symbol resurrected.
The wheel of the windshield over Chlumem turns again after years.
It can be seen from far away because it is located on a fifteen-meter-high stoog.
People in the surrounding area call him “The Wind of the Wind”.
For a village of 150 inhabitants, it even became one of the elements of the municipal emblem, which the municipality received on the occasion of the congregation of natives in 2010.
"We asked for a sign and the windshield we wanted to have on the sign, of course, everyone knows it in the area," said Mayor Jiří Mašek.
The wind pump is a local technical monument.
It is a bit of a memento of the present: it reminds of the time when the people of the country fought for quality drinking water.
It was rare in the past centuries.
It was only in 1910 that the Chlumsky representatives decided on a solution, which then suited until the mid-1980s.
In the village, a seven-meter-deep well was dug.
Three years later, the well was supplemented with a metal structure with a wind pump that pumped water into the reservoir at the highest point of the village, near the church.
"The construction was carried out by Antonín Kunc from Hranic na Morave at a cost of SEK 2,400," the memorial inscription on the ground fence of the construction of the stool reads.
The pump after several repairs and falls of the wind wheel served in 1971.
On May 7, 1973, a new chapter of the water struggle began to be written: that day a new water pipeline began to serve in Chlumu.
The wind pump has only remained a non-functional municipal symbol and a rarity here.
They dominated this year’s family.
It was only in 2008 that the Chlumski decided to repair the wind wheel and put it back into operation.
They made a replica of the original wheel, reduced by half a meter in diameter.
The wheel was installed on the stool, but it had to be lifted down the same year.
The replica manufacturer did not choose a suitable material and the wheel could not resist the wind.
Then the Chlumska dominanta for several years rested dismantled under the roof.
However, since June this year, the bike on the high stojar has been rotating again.
On the occasion of the congregation of the natives, the town allowed the replica of the wheel to be modified and again placed on the top of the iron tower.
But the wheel pulls utility water from the well only into the blind arm.
And over the summer we completely disconnected it because there was little water in the well.
At least it was empty.
"In autumn, we will disconnect the wind wheel axles from the pump in the sack basket again," explained Mayor Mašek.
Chlum is not the only municipality in the Czech Republic where the wind wheel has entered the municipality mark, but it is the only village of this kind in the whole of Vysočině.
A similar element in the sign is in honor of local technical monuments such as in Chvalkovice and Zelené Hory in Vyškovsk, in Kuželovo in Hodonínsk, Partutovic in Přerovsk or in Polica in Vsetínsk.
