At their most anticipated meeting in years, the Federal Reserve legislators will spend two days this week sitting at a 27-foot Honduras mahogany table and deciding whether it’s time to raise a key interest rate after a decade.
Tying above them at one end of the central bank ornament, the two-storey meeting room will be a wall painting of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues have to put the economic interests of the nation above everything else.
The central bank has a double charge from Congress: to maximize U.S. employment and keep prices stable.
But since the Great Recession, Fed officials have recognized that there is an unwritten third term: financial stability.
And this third term could be an X-factor too close to a predictable decision to be announced on Thursday on whether the U.S. economy is ready to kick off with a retreat from an unprecedented stimulus in the form of near-zero short-term interest rates on the spot from the end of 2008.
Although most data shows solid growth in the economy, recent turbulences in the global financial markets could already scare the cautious Fed for adding to volatility by raising its federal fund reference rate – even by no more than a quarter of a percentage point.
"It's clear that the labor market and inflation will be the most important thing to watch first," said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think they’re just looking for an excuse to not raise the rate, the increased uncertainty surrounding the global market already provides them with sufficient justification to wait further,” she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which itself is a cause of nervousness in the financial markets.
About half of the economists recently polled by Blomberg predicted a rate hike this week.
Financial markets, however, expect the Fed to delay the matter, with the key indicator only about 30% chance of rising.
This would indicate a decline in the stock market if the Fed raises interest rates, only if politicians soften the downturn by promising that further increases are in sight.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average jumped 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16.599.85.
The assembly was launched by the expectation that Fed politicians will delay interest rates this week in calm, says John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
“It would be a surprise if the Fed raised interest rates now,” he said.
If the Fed politicians did, “they would have to go to the extreme in their program statement and hold the financial markets in hand to avoid panic.”
Other experts said the rate hike would calm the financial markets, as it would remove the uncertainty about how the Fed would proceed.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed on track to raise interest rates by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of currency conditions that would confirm the strength of the U.S. economic recovery.
Yellen said she expects rates to rise this year over the spring and early summer despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress is needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, the labour market has seen solid growth this year.
The unemployment rate dropped to 5.1% in the previous month, the lowest in more than seven years and is close to the level the Fed considers full employment.
Wage gains showed signs of rise.
And while inflation continues to be below the central bank’s annual 2% target, Fed politicians say the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy “can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the tightness of the labor market,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world began to collapse at the end of last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average dropped up to 16 percent below its record value in May, as investors feared the slowing Chinese economy would drag down global growth.
The market has somewhat rebounded this month and the Dow is now losing only 10% of the May high.
For Fed politicians, the troubled market situation provides a comprehensive calculation of when to start raising interest rates.
“In the absence of what has happened to the financial markets, and reports of the weakness of the Chinese economy in the last few weeks, there would be a tightening at this meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, senior researcher at UCLA’s Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
Now he predicts that they will wait at least a month to gain better control over the consequences.
“There is a lot of uncertainty about what impact it will have on the U.S. economy, and they have almost no data to rely on about the latest developments in China,” Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not one of the Fed’s main interests, so technically it should not be included in their decision-making.
But in fact, the Fed has become the global currency authority.
The influence of the central bank in recent years has been enormous.
The mere hint by then-Chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “strangle” their monetary expansion in the market has triggered cramps around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly closely interconnected, Fed leaders are expected to follow developments elsewhere, but also to consult with other central banks and experts to better understand the state of the global economy.
Their decision-making process is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global wealth-management strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Va., noted this month that “The Fed has a history of exaggerated with movements in financial markets that seem unrelated to economic foundations.”
Lacker, a voting policy maker of the Federal Open Market Committee who pushed for rates to rise, cited the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
