The speed on the highways will remain the same.
Acceleration to 150 km/h was rejected.
On selected sections of the highways, it will not be possible to increase the maximum speed up to 150 km/h under favorable conditions.
On Tuesday, the House adopted an amendment by the Senate, which rejected the increase in speed.
The new law will now go to the President.
President Miloš Zeman said at the end of April that he would veto the law allowing 100km speed.
Minister of Transport Dan Ťok (for ANO) was against the increase, according to which the Czech motorway network is not yet built for such a speed.
On Tuesday, the Senate voted in favour of the bill.
The approved amendment will now allow, in accordance with the original government proposal, to increase the speed from 90 to 110 kilometers per hour on selected first-class roads, especially four-stream roads.
The House initially extended this option to the highways, which could be used in selected sections with speeds up to 150 km/h, but the Senate rejected it.
Members have now agreed to his proposal.
The Senators, with the approval of the Minister of Transport, also removed the authority of the traffic police to have the last word in the modification of local roads, which are cared for by the municipalities.
The Senate version, which was approved by the House, also envisages that sewage, water pipes or public lighting cables can be placed along the road surface.
The municipalities would save money by buying land.
Municipalities should also not have the obligation to take care of road vegetation along local roads regardless of the owner of the respective land.
The novel also aims to help improve the protection of roads and make it easier for municipalities to handle removed vehicles that are not registered by owners.
In addition, municipalities will be able to sell removed vehicles for which their owners will not register within a six-month period after the notice of removal.
Municipalities will be able to exclude transit freight traffic across their territory on second and third-class roads under the threat of fines for shipping companies.
The new law also eliminates the possibility of introducing electronic highway signs instead of the previous paper signs, which will be used after 1 January next year.
According to the government, this will save money for the introduction of the electronic system.
