For mildly obese diabetics, weight loss surgery could be useful
The benefits of weight loss surgery for moderately obese people with type 2 diabetes may last for at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is still too early to say whether moderate obese people with type 2 diabetes live longer after weight loss surgery than those receiving non-surgical treatment.
“Mortality data takes a long time to show,” says Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in weight loss surgery who wrote the introduction to the new JAMA surgery study.
Operations for weight loss, bariatric surgery use various methods to reduce the stomach.
Reducing hunger and limiting the human body to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most of the research has been conducted on people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 25 or higher.
BMI, which measures the weight ratio related to height, is considered normal in values between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or higher indicates an overweight person, and people above 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For their new study, researchers from General Hospital Min-Sheng in Taiwan used data collected from a study since 2007 that deals with two types of bariatric surgery – stomach bypass and gastrectomy – in treatment procedures for type 3 diabetes in people who were mildly obese.
The average BMI among those who underwent surgery fell from 31 to 24.5 at the end of their fifth year, according to the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI of those who did not receive surgical treatment for diabetes remained roughly the same at 29.
Among patients with surgery, diabetes was resolved completely in 36 percent and partially in 28 cases.
In the drug-treated group, for comparison, diabetes was solved completely in only 1 percent and partially only in about 2 percent of patients.
Furthermore, blood pressure, triglyceride and “bad” LDL cholesterol controls were shown to be “generally better in the surgical group,” the authors found.
The researchers also monitored the patient’s hemoglobin A1c levels in the blood, which reflects the ongoing blood sugar levels in the body.
Hemoglobin A1c is best kept below 7 percent, researchers say.
After surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c level dropped from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
In the drug-treated group, however, this figure remained at about 8 percent.
But this better “glycemic control” – which is reflected in better hemoglobin A1c levels – did not reduce mortality in five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared average results with two types of operations.
After the fifth year, the bypass group lost more weight compared to the gastrectomy group (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), achieved greater decreases in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1 percent versus 2.1 percent) and were more likely to have diabetes remission (46.9 percent versus 16.7 percent).
While a new study does not show improvement in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of stronger people in Sweden where they found that surgery leads to prolonged life, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona College or Medicine-Phoenix.
According to a Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery had about 29 percent more chances of surviving in the next 15 years, compared to the group that tried more conventional methods.
Although a new study did not show any improvement in survival among patients after surgery, according to Blackstone, this is a reassuring outcome for people with a BMI below 35 who are interested in these procedures.
"Here this work is critical because it states that surgery is safer in a group with a lower BMI," without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, he states.
Blackstone also further argues that people and their doctors should start taking weight really seriously after a patient’s BMI drops between 27 and 30.
“I think we’re waiting too long to show people the seriousness of the situation,” he says.
