Xi calls for opening the economy to the world
It is necessary to open the economy to the wider world to boost growth, President Xi Jinping told a group whose task is Tuesday’s governance reform.
“China should engage in attracting foreign investment and expertise and improve open policies,” he said on the 16th meeting of the Central Leadership Group on Deepening Global Reform.
Promoting openness in the coming reforms will give new momentum and vitality, as well as a new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The Leading Group has adopted a number of guidelines, including a negative list of regulatory market access, the easing of border control policies, the support of state-owned enterprises (SOE) to absorb private capital, and the reorganization of the resident registration system.
The statement states that a negative list will be drawn up to identify sectors and enterprises that are outside the investment limits.
This system will be gradually tested and improved through trial programs.
This step is significant because it will give the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensuring a legal business environment and making the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also release controls on the powers it delegates to companies and ensure that the companies themselves decide how to run their business.
The statement also states that China will allow border regions to discover new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
In an effort to open up the state-controlled sector, more areas will be opened to private investment.
“The government will not change its policy towards foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of companies that are financed from abroad and will provide them with better services,” the statement said.
In addition, it will be easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or a “green card,” thanks to the optimization of requirements and the simplification of the application process.
Ensuring the rights of lawyers to practice and develop professional judges and prosecutors was also discussed at the meeting.
Prime Minister Li Keqiang and leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli also attended the meeting, according to a statement issued after the meeting.
